## Polygon: A Fundamental Plane Figure Bounded by Line Segments

For other uses, see [Polygon (disambiguation)](/Polygon_(disambiguation)).

Some polygons of different kinds: open (excluding its boundary), boundary only (excluding interior), closed (including both boundary and interior), and self-intersecting.

In the realm of [geometry](/Geometry), where forms and spaces are meticulously defined, a [polygon](/Polygon) stands as a foundational concept: a [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)) [figure](/Shape) constructed entirely from a finite sequence of straight [line segments](/Line_segment). These segments are not haphazardly arranged; they are connected end-to-end to elegantly form a [closed polygonal chain](/Closed_polygonal_chain). This closure is paramount, distinguishing a polygon from a mere sequence of lines. To exist as a polygon, the figure must completely enclose a region, returning to its starting point without ambiguity.

The individual straight [line segments](/Line_segment) that constitute this [closed polygonal chain](/Closed_polygonal_chain) are formally recognized as its [edges](/Edge_(geometry)), or more colloquially, its sides. The precise points where any two consecutive [edges](/Edge_(geometry)) converge and meet are termed the polygon's [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) or corners. The nomenclature for polygons is often straightforward, determined by the count of these sides: an *n*-gon denotes a polygon possessing *n* sides. For instance, a [triangle](/Triangle), the simplest Euclidean polygon, is a 3-gon, while a [quadrilateral](/Quadrilateral) is a 4-gon, and so on.

A particularly well-behaved category of polygons is the [simple polygon](/Simple_polygon). This designation applies to any polygon that, in its construction, does not intersect itself. To be more precise, the only permissible intersections among the [line segments](/Line_segment) forming the polygon are the shared endpoints of consecutive segments within the polygonal chain. When one speaks of a [simple polygon](/Simple_polygon), one is often referring to the boundary that encloses a distinct region of the [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)). This enclosed region itself is referred to as a solid polygon, or its interior, known as its body, a polygonal region, or polygonal area. In practical contexts, particularly when the discussion implicitly concerns only these [simple](/Simple_polygon) and solid forms, the term "polygon" frequently serves as a shorthand for either a [simple polygon](/Simple_polygon) (the boundary) or a solid polygon (the enclosed region). Such precision is often lost on the casual observer, but its importance is fundamental.

However, not all polygons adhere to such pristine simplicity. A [polygonal chain](/Closed_polygonal_chain) possesses the geometric freedom to cross over itself, giving rise to more intricate forms such as [star polygons](/Star_polygon) and other varieties of [self-intersecting polygons](/List_of_self-intersecting_polygons). These figures, while still defined by connected [line segments](/Line_segment) and closure, introduce complexities in how their "interior" is perceived and measured. Furthermore, some mathematical frameworks extend the definition of a polygon beyond the confines of a single [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)). In these contexts, [closed polygonal chains](/Closed_polygonal_chain) existing within [Euclidean space](/Euclidean_space) (or even higher-dimensional spaces) are considered a type of polygon, specifically a [skew polygon](/Skew_polygon), even when their [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) do not all reside on a common [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)). This broader perspective acknowledges the form's inherent structure regardless of its spatial embedding.

Ultimately, a polygon can be understood as a 2-dimensional manifestation of the more encompassing concept of a [polytope](/Polytope), which generalizes this idea to any number of dimensions. Just as a polygon defines a boundary and an interior in two dimensions, a [polytope](/Polytope) does so in *n* dimensions. The elegance of mathematics, it seems, is in its recursive definitions. And, as is often the case with fundamental ideas, numerous other generalizations of polygons have been meticulously defined over time, each serving specific, often esoteric, purposes.

### Etymology

The very word "polygon" carries its meaning within its ancient roots, a testament to the straightforwardness of early geometric observation. It descends from the [Greek](/Greek_language) adjective *πολύς* (pronounced *polús*), meaning 'much' or 'many', combined with *γωνία* (pronounced *gōnía*), which translates to 'corner' or 'angle'. Thus, a polygon is, quite literally, a "many-cornered" or "many-angled" figure. A perfectly descriptive, if rather uninspired, name. Interestingly, some etymological analyses have also posited that *γόνυ* (pronounced *gónu*), meaning 'knee', might be a potential origin for the 'gon' component, perhaps alluding to the bending or articulation at a polygon's [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)). While a charming thought, it hardly changes the fundamental truth of its definition.

### Classification

Polygons, like all things in a structured universe, can be categorized, their properties dissected and assigned to neatly labeled boxes. This classification allows for a more rigorous understanding of their diverse forms, moving beyond merely counting their sides.

Some different types of polygon

#### Number of sides

The most immediate and fundamental method of classifying polygons is, predictably, by the sheer quantity of their sides. An *n*-gon is simply a polygon with *n* sides, a system that, while lacking in poetic flourish, is undeniably effective. This count directly dictates the number of [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) and, in most cases, the fundamental geometric properties of the figure.

#### Convexity and intersection

Beyond the simple count of sides, polygons are frequently characterized by their overall shape, specifically concerning their [convexity](/Convex_polygon) or the particular nature of their non-convexity. This defines how the figure "bends" or "folds" in on itself.

*   **[Convex](/Convex_polygon)**: A polygon is deemed [convex](/Convex_polygon) if, and only if, any straight [line](/Line_(geometry)) drawn completely through its interior (and not merely tangent to an [edge](/Edge_(geometry)) or [vertex](/Vertex_(geometry))) will invariably intersect its boundary at precisely two points. This property has several direct consequences: all of its [interior angles](/Interior_angle) must be strictly less than 180°, and, perhaps more intuitively, any [line segment](/Line_segment) connecting two points on the polygon's boundary will lie entirely within or on the boundary of the polygon itself. There are no "indentations" or "caves" in a [convex polygon](/Convex_polygon). This condition holds true for polygons irrespective of the underlying geometry, not exclusively in [Euclidean geometry](/Euclidean_geometry). It represents a robust and well-behaved form, the geometric ideal, if you will.

*   **Non-convex**: As the name rather plainly suggests, a non-convex polygon is simply one that fails the criteria for [convexity](/Convex_polygon). This means that at least one line can be found that intersects its boundary more than twice, or, equivalently, a [line segment](/Line_segment) can be drawn between two points on its boundary that, at some point, passes outside the polygon's defined interior. These are the polygons with quirks, deviations from the perfectly rounded ideal.

*   **[Simple](/Simple_polygon)**: A [simple polygon](/Simple_polygon) is characterized by a boundary that does not intersect itself at any point other than its [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)). All [convex polygons](/Convex_polygon) are, by definition, simple. This category represents the most commonly visualized and studied polygons, forming a single, unbroken loop.

*   **[Concave](/Concave_polygon)**: This is a specific subset of non-convex polygons, distinguished by being both non-convex *and* [simple](/Simple_polygon). The defining feature of a [concave polygon](/Concave_polygon) is the presence of at least one [interior angle](/Interior_angle) that measures greater than 180°. These are the polygons that appear to have been "pushed in" or "dented" from the outside.

*   **[Star-shaped](/Star-shaped_polygon)**: A polygon is considered [star-shaped](/Star-shaped_polygon) if its entire interior is visible from at least one internal point, without any of the polygon's [edges](/Edge_(geometry)) obstructing the view. This implies that the polygon must be [simple](/Simple_polygon), but it can be either [convex](/Convex_polygon) or [concave](/Concave_polygon). All [convex polygons](/Convex_polygon) are inherently [star-shaped](/Star-shaped_polygon), as every point within a [convex polygon](/Convex_polygon) can "see" the entire interior.

*   **[Self-intersecting](/List_of_self-intersecting_polygons)**: These polygons venture into more complex territory, where the boundary itself crosses over itself. The term "complex" is occasionally employed as a contrast to "simple" in this context, but such usage risks creating confusion with the more specialized concept of a [complex polygon](/Complex_polytope), which exists in the abstract realm of the [complex Hilbert plane](/Hilbert_space) and involves two [complex](/Complex_number) dimensions, a notion far removed from the simple visual intersection. Such semantic nuances are, of course, a constant joy.

*   **[Star polygon](/Star_polygon)**: A [star polygon](/Star_polygon) is a specific type of [self-intersecting polygon](/List_of_self-intersecting_polygons) that exhibits a regular, symmetrical pattern of self-intersection. It's a common misconception, or perhaps just wishful thinking, that a polygon can be both a star *and* [star-shaped](/Star-shaped_polygon). These are distinct properties; a [star polygon](/Star_polygon) self-intersects, while a [star-shaped polygon](/Star-shaped_polygon) is [simple](/Simple_polygon) but may be [concave](/Concave_polygon).

#### Equality and symmetry

Further refinements in classification arise from the inherent symmetries and equalities within a polygon's structure, elevating some forms above the mundane.

*   **[Equiangular](/Equiangular_polygon)**: In an [equiangular polygon](/Equiangular_polygon), every single [corner angle](/Interior_angle) possesses the exact same measure. A pleasing uniformity, to be sure.

*   **[Equilateral](/Equilateral_polygon)**: An [equilateral polygon](/Equilateral_polygon) is defined by having all of its [edges](/Edge_(geometry)) (or sides) of precisely the same length. A balance of dimensions.

*   **[Regular](/Regular_polygon)**: The paragon of polygonal forms, a [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) is one that is simultaneously both [equilateral](/Equilateral_polygon) and [equiangular](/Equiangular_polygon). These are the perfectly balanced, aesthetically pleasing shapes that often come to mind when one first considers polygons.

*   **[Cyclic](/Cyclic_polygon)**: A [cyclic polygon](/Cyclic_polygon) is one whose [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) all lie precisely upon a single [circle](/Circle). This encompassing circle is known as the [circumcircle](/Circumcircle) of the polygon.

*   **[Tangential](/Tangential_polygon)**: Conversely, a [tangential polygon](/Tangential_polygon) is defined by the property that all of its sides are tangent to a single [inscribed circle](/Inscribed_circle) within its interior.

*   **Isogonal or [vertex-transitive](/Vertex-transitive)**: In an isogonal polygon, all of its [corners](/Vertex_(geometry)) are indistinguishable under the polygon's [symmetry operations](/Symmetry_orbit); they lie within the same [symmetry orbit](/Symmetry_orbit). Such a polygon is necessarily both [cyclic](/Cyclic_polygon) and [equiangular](/Equiangular_polygon).

*   **Isotoxal or [edge-transitive](/Edge-transitive)**: An isotoxal polygon is one where all of its sides are congruent and lie within the same [symmetry orbit](/Symmetry_orbit). This type of polygon is consequently both [equilateral](/Equilateral_polygon) and [tangential](/Tangential_polygon).

The property of regularity, that coveted state of geometric perfection, can be expressed through these symmetry properties as well: a polygon achieves regularity if and only if it is simultaneously both isogonal and isotoxal. Equivalently, it is regular if it is both [cyclic](/Cyclic_polygon) and [equilateral](/Equilateral_polygon). A curious exception to the usual visual order is the non-convex regular polygon, which is famously referred to as a regular [star polygon](/Star_polygon), maintaining its internal symmetries despite its self-intersections.

#### Miscellaneous

Beyond these primary categorizations, other properties allow for further, more specialized descriptions of polygons.

*   **[Rectilinear](/Rectilinear_polygon)**: A [rectilinear polygon](/Rectilinear_polygon) is defined by the rather rigid constraint that all of its sides meet at precise right angles. This means every one of its [interior angles](/Interior_angle) will be either 90° or 270°. These are the polygons that adhere strictly to a grid, devoid of any sloping lines.

*   **[Monotone](/Monotone_polygon) with respect to a given line L**: This is a more topological classification. A polygon is [monotone](/Monotone_polygon) with respect to a given [line](/Line_(geometry)) *L* if every line [orthogonal](/Orthogonal_(geometry)) (perpendicular) to *L* intersects the polygon's boundary no more than twice. This essentially means the polygon "flows" in a consistent direction relative to *L*, without doubling back on itself excessively.

### Properties and formulas

For the sake of clarity and consistency, and perhaps a slight aversion to unnecessary complications, [Euclidean geometry](/Euclidean_geometry) is assumed throughout the following discussion. Deviations from this standard are, as always, noted.

Partitioning an n -gon into n − 2 triangles

#### Angles

Every polygon, by its very definition, possesses an equal number of [corners](/Vertex_(geometry)) and sides. Each of these [corners](/Vertex_(geometry)) is associated with several angles, the two most commonly discussed being the interior and exterior angles.

*   **[Interior angle](/Interior_angle)** – The sum of the [interior angles](/Interior_angle) of any [simple n-gon](/Simple_polygon) (a polygon with *n* sides) is invariably given by the formula ( *n* − 2) × [π](/Pi) [radians](/Radian), which translates to ( *n* − 2) × 180 [degrees](/Degree_(angle)). This fundamental property arises from the elegant observation that any [simple n-gon](/Simple_polygon) can be decomposed, or triangulated, into precisely (*n* − 2) [triangles](/Triangle), and each [triangle](/Triangle) itself possesses an [angle sum](/Interior_angle) of [π](/Pi) [radians](/Radian) or 180 [degrees](/Degree_(angle)). It's a neat trick, if you appreciate such things. For a [convex regular n-gon](/Regular_polygon), where all angles are equal, the measure of any single [interior angle](/Interior_angle) can be calculated as:

    $$ \left(1-{\tfrac {2}{n}}\right)\pi $$
    [radians](/Radian) or
    $$ 180-{\tfrac {360}{n}} $$
    [degrees](/Degree_(angle)).

    The [interior angles](/Interior_angle) of regular [star polygons](/Star_polygon)—those fascinating, self-intersecting forms—were first systematically investigated by [Louis Poinsot](/Louis_Poinsot). In the very paper where he meticulously described the four [regular star polyhedra](/Kepler%E2%80%93Poinsot_polyhedron), he provided the formula for these angles. For a regular
    $$ {\tfrac {p}{q}} $$
    -gon (which is a *p*-gon with a central [density](/Density_(polytope)) of *q*), each [interior angle](/Interior_angle) is given by:
    $$ {\tfrac {\pi (p-2q)}{p}} $$
    [radians](/Radian) or
    $$ {\tfrac {180(p-2q)}{p}} $$
    [degrees](/Degree_(angle)). It's a formula that hints at the underlying order even in seemingly chaotic forms.

*   **[Exterior angle](/Exterior_angle)** – The [exterior angle](/Exterior_angle) at a [vertex](/Vertex_(geometry)) is, by definition, the [supplementary angle](/Supplementary_angle) to the [interior angle](/Interior_angle) at that same [vertex](/Vertex_(geometry)). Consider the simple act of tracing the perimeter of a [convex n-gon](/Convex_polygon): as you navigate each [corner](/Vertex_(geometry)), you "turn" by a specific amount. This amount is precisely the [exterior angle](/Exterior_angle). If you complete a full circuit around the entire polygon, you will have executed one full [turn](/Turn_(geometry)). Consequently, the sum of all the [exterior angles](/Exterior_angle) of any [convex polygon](/Convex_polygon) must always be 360°. This elegant principle can be extended to include [concave simple polygons](/Concave_polygon), provided that external angles corresponding to turns in the opposite direction are subtracted from the cumulative total. When tracing around an *n*-gon in its most general sense, encompassing even [self-intersecting polygons](/List_of_self-intersecting_polygons), the sum of the [exterior angles](/Exterior_angle) (representing the total angular rotation accumulated at the [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry))) can be any integer multiple *d* of 360°. Here, *d* is a significant topological invariant known as the [density](/Density_(polytope)) or [turning number](/Turning_number) of the polygon. For example, a [pentagram](/Pentagram) has a [turning number](/Turning_number) of 2, resulting in an exterior angle sum of 720°, while a degenerate angular "eight" or [antiparallelogram](/Antiparallelogram) can have a [turning number](/Turning_number) of 0.

#### Area

Coordinates of a non-convex pentagon

Calculating the [area](/Area_(geometry)) enclosed by a polygon is a fundamental geometric problem, one that becomes particularly interesting when dealing with irregular or complex shapes. In this section, we assume the [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) of the polygon are ordered sequentially as
$$ (x_{0},y_{0}),(x_{1},y_{1}),\ldots ,(x_{n-1},y_{n-1}) $$
. For the sake of mathematical convenience in certain formulas, it is customary to denote
$$ (x_{n},y_{n}) = (x_{0},y_{0}) $$
, effectively closing the loop.

##### Simple polygons

*   Further information: [Shoelace formula](/Shoelace_formula)

If the polygon in question is non-self-intersecting—that is, a [simple polygon](/Simple_polygon)—its signed [area](/Area_(geometry)) *A* can be elegantly computed using the following formula:

$$ A={\frac {1}{2}}\sum _{i=0}^{n-1}(x_{i}y_{i+1}-x_{i+1}y_{i})\quad {\text{where }}x_{n}=x_{0}{\text{ and }}y_{n}=y_{0}, $$

Alternatively, and perhaps with a touch more algebraic flair, one can employ [determinants](/Determinant):

$$ 16A^{2}=\sum _{i=0}^{n-1}\sum _{j=0}^{n-1}{\begin{vmatrix}Q_{i,j}&Q_{i,j+1}\\Q_{i+1,j}&Q_{i+1,j+1}\end{vmatrix}}, $$

where
$$ Q_{i,j} $$
represents the squared [Euclidean distance](/Euclidean_distance) between [vertex](/Vertex_(geometry))
$$ (x_{i},y_{i}) $$
and [vertex](/Vertex_(geometry))
$$ (x_{j},y_{j}) $$
. This particular formulation, while less common, highlights deeper mathematical connections.

The resultant signed [area](/Area_(geometry)) is contingent upon the specific ordering of the [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) and the chosen [orientation](/Orientation_(vector_space)) of the [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)). Conventionally, the positive [orientation](/Orientation_(vector_space)) is established by a counterclockwise rotation that maps the positive x-axis to the positive y-axis. If the [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) are listed in a counterclockwise sequence (i.e., according to this positive [orientation](/Orientation_(vector_space))), the signed [area](/Area_(geometry)) will be positive. Conversely, if the [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) are ordered clockwise, the signed [area](/Area_(geometry)) will be negative. In either scenario, the absolute value of the result provides the true geometric [area](/Area_(geometry)). This versatile formula is widely known as the [shoelace formula](/Shoelace_formula) or the surveyor's formula, a moniker derived from the crisscrossing pattern of its terms, reminiscent of tying a shoelace. It's a rather practical piece of mathematics, surprisingly useful for something so abstract.

The [area](/Area_(geometry)) *A* of a [simple polygon](/Simple_polygon) can also be determined if one possesses knowledge of the lengths of its sides, denoted as *a*<sub>1</sub>, *a*<sub>2</sub>, ..., *a*<sub>n</sub>, along with its [exterior angles](/Exterior_angle), *θ*<sub>1</sub>, *θ*<sub>2</sub>, ..., *θ*<sub>n</sub>. The formula, though more elaborate, offers an alternative perspective:

$$ {\begin{aligned}A={\frac {1}{2}}(a_{1}[a_{2}\sin(\theta _{1})+a_{3}\sin(\theta _{1}+\theta _{2})+\cdots +a_{n-1}\sin(\theta _{1}+\theta _{2}+\cdots +\theta _{n-2})]\\{}+a_{2}[a_{3}\sin(\theta _{2})+a_{4}\sin(\theta _{2}+\theta _{3})+\cdots +a_{n-1}\sin(\theta _{2}+\cdots +\theta _{n-2})]\\{}+\cdots +a_{n-2}[a_{n-1}\sin(\theta _{n-2})]).\end{aligned}}} $$

This formula was meticulously described by A.M. Lopshits in 1963, adding another tool to the geometrician's arsenal.

For polygons that are specifically drawn on an equally spaced grid, where all of their [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) perfectly align with grid points, a delightfully simple and elegant formula emerges: [Pick's theorem](/Pick%27s_theorem). This theorem states that the polygon's [area](/Area_(geometry)) can be calculated directly from the number of interior grid points (*I*) and boundary grid points (*B*): *A* = *I* + *B*/2 − 1. It's a charmingly direct way to quantify space for those who appreciate a well-defined lattice.

Furthermore, for every polygon with a perimeter *p* and an [area](/Area_(geometry)) *A*, the fundamental [isoperimetric inequality](/Isoperimetric_inequality) holds true:

$$ p^{2}>4\pi A $$

This inequality reveals a profound relationship, demonstrating that among all shapes with a given perimeter, the [circle](/Circle) encloses the maximum [area](/Area_(geometry)). All other polygons, by their very nature, are less efficient in this regard.

In a more abstract but equally fascinating vein, the [Bolyai–Gerwien theorem](/Bolyai%E2%80%93Gerwien_theorem) asserts that for any two [simple polygons](/Simple_polygon) that possess identical [area](/Area_(geometry)), the first polygon can always be meticulously dissected into a finite number of polygonal pieces. These pieces can then be rearranged, without any overlap or gaps, to perfectly form the second polygon. This theorem speaks to a deep equivalence between shapes that share the same measure of space, a testament to the transformative power of dissection.

It is a common oversight, often leading to erroneous assumptions, that the lengths of a polygon's sides are sufficient to determine its [area](/Area_(geometry)). In general, this is not the case; a polygon can often be "flexed" or reshaped while maintaining side lengths, thus altering its enclosed [area](/Area_(geometry)). However, if a polygon is both [simple](/Simple_polygon) and [cyclic](/Cyclic_polygon)—meaning its [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) lie on a [circle](/Circle)—then, and only then, do its side lengths uniquely define its [area](/Area_(geometry)). Among all *n*-gons with a specified set of side lengths, the one that encloses the greatest [area](/Area_(geometry)) is always the [cyclic](/Cyclic_polygon) one. Moreover, for all *n*-gons sharing a given perimeter, the polygon that achieves the maximum [area](/Area_(geometry)) is the [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) (which, by definition, is also [cyclic](/Cyclic_polygon)). It seems regularity, once again, leads to optimal efficiency.

##### Regular polygons

Many specialized and often more concise formulas are applicable specifically to the [areas](/Area_(geometry)) of [regular polygons](/Regular_polygon), simplifying calculations for these ideal forms.

The [area](/Area_(geometry)) *A* of a [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) can be expressed elegantly in terms of *r*, the radius of its [inscribed circle](/Inscribed_circle) (the largest circle that can fit entirely within the polygon and be tangent to all its sides), and *p*, its perimeter:

$$ A={\tfrac {1}{2}}\cdot p\cdot r. $$

This radius *r* is also frequently referred to as the polygon's [apothem](/Apothem) and is often denoted by the variable *a*.

Alternatively, the [area](/Area_(geometry)) *A* of a [regular n-gon](/Regular_polygon) can be calculated using *R*, the radius of its [circumscribed circle](/Circumcircle) (the unique circle that passes through all of the [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) of the [regular n-gon](/Regular_polygon)):

$$ A=R^{2}\cdot {\frac {n}{2}}\cdot \sin {\frac {2\pi }{n}}=R^{2}\cdot n\cdot \sin {\frac {\pi }{n}}\cdot \cos {\frac {\pi }{n}} $$

These formulas highlight the deep connection between [regular polygons](/Regular_polygon) and [circles](/Circle). Indeed, as the number of sides *n* of a [regular polygon](/Regular_polygon) approaches infinity, the polygon itself approaches the form of a [circle](/Circle), and its [area](/Area_(geometry)) formula converges to the familiar [area](/Area_(geometry)) of a [circle](/Circle) with radius *R*:
$$ \lim _{n\to +\infty }R^{2}\cdot {\frac {n}{2}}\cdot \sin {\frac {2\pi }{n}}=\pi \cdot R^{2} $$
. A neat demonstration of limits, if you're into that sort of thing.

##### Self-intersecting

The concept of [area](/Area_(geometry)) becomes significantly more ambiguous and requires careful definition when dealing with [self-intersecting polygons](/Complex_polygon). The very act of the boundary crossing itself complicates what constitutes "inside" and "outside," leading to at least two distinct interpretations, each yielding a different result.

*   One definition employs the same formulas used for [simple polygons](/Simple_polygon), but with an important modification: particular regions within the polygon are assigned a "density" factor, which effectively multiplies their contribution to the total [area](/Area_(geometry)). For example, the central [convex pentagon](/Convex_polygon) that forms the core of a [pentagram](/Pentagram) is considered to have a [density](/Density_(polytope)) of 2, meaning its [area](/Area_(geometry)) is counted twice. In the case of a cross-quadrilateral (a figure resembling an "8"), the two triangular regions formed by the self-intersection are assigned opposite-signed densities. When their areas are summed, this can result in a total [area](/Area_(geometry)) of zero for the entire figure, which, while mathematically consistent, can be counter-intuitive.

*   A second approach considers the enclosed regions as actual point sets. Under this definition, the [area](/Area_(geometry)) is simply the measure of the total [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)) covered by the polygon, regardless of how many times the boundary crosses over itself. This corresponds to calculating the [area](/Area_(geometry)) of one or more [simple polygons](/Simple_polygon) that share the exact same outline as the [self-intersecting polygon](/Complex_polygon), effectively ignoring the self-intersections for the purpose of defining the boundary. For the cross-quadrilateral, this means it would be treated as two distinct [simple triangles](/Triangle), and their absolute areas would be summed. This method often aligns more closely with intuitive notions of "space occupied."

#### Centroid

The [centroid](/Centroid) of a polygon represents its geometric center, a point of balance. As with [area](/Area_(geometry)), its calculation depends on whether one is considering the solid polygon or merely its set of [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)). Using the same convention for [vertex](/Vertex_(geometry)) coordinates as established in the preceding section, the coordinates of the [centroid](/Centroid)
$$ (C_x, C_y) $$
of a solid [simple polygon](/Simple_polygon) are given by:

$$ C_{x}={\frac {1}{6A}}\sum _{i=0}^{n-1}(x_{i}+x_{i+1})(x_{i}y_{i+1}-x_{i+1}y_{i}), $$

$$ C_{y}={\frac {1}{6A}}\sum _{i=0}^{n-1}(y_{i}+y_{i+1})(x_{i}y_{i+1}-x_{i+1}y_{i}). $$

It is crucial to note that in these formulas, the signed value of the [area](/Area_(geometry))
$$ A $$
(as obtained from the [shoelace formula](/Shoelace_formula)) must be utilized. Failure to do so will, predictably, yield incorrect results.

For [triangles](/Triangle) (*n* = 3), a unique simplification occurs: the [centroid](/Centroid) of the [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) and the [centroid](/Centroid) of the solid triangular shape coincide perfectly. However, this convenient equivalence is generally not true for polygons with *n* > 3 sides. For polygons with more than three sides, the two centroids are distinct. The [centroid](/Centroid) of the vertex set of a polygon with *n* [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) is simply the average of their coordinates:

$$ c_{x}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=0}^{n-1}x_{i}, $$

$$ c_{y}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=0}^{n-1}y_{i}. $$

This distinction between the center of the boundary points and the center of the enclosed mass is a subtle but important one, often overlooked by those who prefer simple answers.

### Generalizations

The concept of a polygon, while seemingly straightforward in its [Euclidean plane](/Euclidean_geometry) form, has been ingeniously expanded and generalized in numerous ways by mathematicians, pushing the boundaries of what a "many-sided figure" can entail. Because, apparently, the simple reality wasn't enough.

*   A **[spherical polygon](/Spherical_polygon)** ventures beyond the flat [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)), existing instead on the curved surface of a [sphere](/Sphere). It is defined as a circuit of arcs of great [circles](/Circle) (which serve as its sides) connecting a sequence of [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) that lie on the [sphere's surface](/Sphere). This generalization is particularly notable because it permits the existence of the [digon](/Digon), a polygon with only two sides and two corners, a configuration utterly impossible in a flat [Euclidean plane](/Euclidean_geometry). [Spherical polygons](/Spherical_polygon) are not mere curiosities; they play a critical role in fields such as [cartography](/Cartography) (the art and science of map making), where the Earth's curved surface necessitates such geometric adaptations, and in [Wythoff's construction](/Wythoff%27s_construction) of the [uniform polyhedra](/Uniform_polyhedra).

*   A **[skew polygon](/Skew_polygon)** is a polygon that refuses to be confined to a single [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)). Instead, its [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry)) and [edges](/Edge_(geometry)) zigzag through three (or even more) dimensions. While its [edges](/Edge_(geometry)) are still straight [line segments](/Line_segment) and it forms a [closed polygonal chain](/Closed_polygonal_chain), the entire figure does not lie flat. The [Petrie polygons](/Petrie_polygon) of the regular [polytopes](/Polytope) (higher-dimensional analogues of polygons and [polyhedra](/Polyhedron)) are well-known and visually striking examples of [skew polygons](/Skew_polygon).

*   An **[apeirogon](/Apeirogon)**, from the Greek "apeiros" meaning infinite, is a degenerate polygon of infinitely many sides. It represents an infinite sequence of sides and angles, which, by its very nature, is not closed in the traditional sense but also possesses no ends, extending indefinitely in both directions. It's what happens when you decide "many" isn't quite enough.

*   A **[skew apeirogon](/Skew_apeirogon)** takes the concept of the [apeirogon](/Apeirogon) and lifts it out of the [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)). It is an infinite sequence of sides and angles that, like its finite [skew polygon](/Skew_polygon) counterpart, does not lie within a single flat [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)).

*   A **[polygon with holes](/Polygon_with_holes)** describes a region of the [plane](/Plane_(mathematics)) that is connected (meaning you can travel between any two points within it without leaving the region) but is "multiply-connected" topologically. It possesses one external boundary, defining its overall shape, and one or more interior boundaries, which are the "holes" within it. Imagine a doughnut, but flat and with straight sides.

*   A **[complex polygon](/Complex_polytope)** is a more abstract and algebraic generalization. It is a [configuration](/Configuration_(polytope)) that is analogous to an ordinary polygon but exists within the [complex plane](/Complex_plane)—a mathematical space composed of two [real](/Real_number) dimensions and two [imaginary](/Imaginary_number) dimensions. This moves polygons far beyond simple visualization and into the realm of abstract algebra and higher-dimensional geometry.

*   An **[abstract polygon](/Abstract_polytope)** strips away all geometric properties, focusing purely on the combinatorial relationships between its elements. It is an algebraic [partially ordered set](/Partially_ordered_set) that meticulously represents the various constituent elements of a polygon (such as its sides and [vertices](/Vertex_(geometry))) and their intricate connectivity. A "real" geometric polygon, the kind one can draw or visualize, is then considered a "realization" of its associated [abstract polygon](/Abstract_polytope). Depending on the specific mapping or "realization," all the geometric generalizations described here can be understood as manifestations of their underlying [abstract polygon](/Abstract_polytope) structures.

*   A **[polyhedron](/Polyhedron)** extends the concept of a polygon into three dimensions. It is a three-dimensional solid bounded by flat polygonal faces, acting as the direct three-dimensional analogue to a polygon in two dimensions. These faces are themselves polygons. The corresponding shapes in four or higher dimensions are generally referred to as [polytopes](/Polytope). (It's worth noting that in some alternative conventions, the terms "[polyhedron](/Polyhedron)" and "[polytope](/Polytope)" are used more broadly to refer to such figures in any dimension, with the primary distinction often being that a [polytope](/Polytope) is necessarily bounded, while a [polyhedron](/Polyhedron) might not be.)

### Naming

The convention for naming polygons, much like their definition, is rooted in [Late Latin](/Late_Latin) and [Greek](/Greek_language). The word *polygōnum* (a noun in [Late Latin](/Late_Latin)) stems from the [Greek](/Greek_language) *πολύγωνον* (polygōnon/polugōnon), which, when used as a noun, is the neuter form of the masculine adjective *πολύγωνος* (polygōnos/polugōnos), meaning "many-angled." A rather literal lineage.

Individual polygons are typically named, and sometimes classified, based on the number of sides they possess. This involves combining a [Greek](/Greek_language)-derived [numerical prefix](/Numerical_prefix) with the suffix "-gon." For example, a 5-sided polygon is a [pentagon](/Pentagon), and a 12-sided polygon is a [dodecagon](/Dodecagon). However, there are a few notable exceptions to this otherwise consistent system: the [triangle](/Triangle) (3 sides), [quadrilateral](/Quadrilateral) (4 sides), and [nonagon](/Nonagon) (9 sides) employ Latin or unique English roots for their common names, though their Greek-derived alternatives (trigon, tetragon, enneagon, respectively) are also recognized, if less frequently used.

Beyond the relatively common [decagons](/Decagon) (10-sided) and [dodecagons](/Dodecagon) (12-sided), mathematicians, perhaps weary of inventing increasingly convoluted Greek-Latin hybrid names, generally resort to a simpler, more pragmatic numerical notation. Thus, one typically refers to a 17-gon or a 257-gon, a clear indication that practicality often trumps linguistic elegance in higher mathematics.

Nevertheless, exceptions persist for side counts that are readily expressed in verbal form (such as "20-gon" for [icosagon](/Icosagon) or "30-gon" for [triacontagon](/Triacontagon)), particularly when used by non-mathematicians who might find "icosagon" less intuitive. Furthermore, some special polygons have earned their own distinct and memorable names. A prime example is the [regular](/Regular_polygon) [star](/Star_polygon) [pentagon](/Pentagon), which is more widely recognized as a [pentagram](/Pentagram) or pentacle, a name imbued with cultural and historical significance far beyond its geometric definition.

